      <hedline>
        <hl1>A World of Wizards And 13-Year-Olds</hl1>
      </hedline>
      <abstract>
        <p>Letter from 13-year-old Martha Bedford opposes adapting language of Harry Potter books from English to American (July 10 Peter H Gleick Op-Ed article)</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>I am a 13-year-old English girl who arrived yesterday to visit my grandparents on Long Island. I spent the whole plane journey reading the new Harry Potter book. This morning we read ''Harry Potter, Minus a Certain Flavour,'' Peter H. Gleick's July 10 Op-Ed article about adapting the language of Harry Potter from English to American.</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>I am a 13-year-old English girl who arrived yesterday to visit my grandparents on Long Island. I spent the whole plane journey reading the new Harry Potter book. This morning we read ''Harry Potter, Minus a Certain Flavour,'' Peter H. Gleick's July 10 Op-Ed article about adapting the language of Harry Potter from English to American.</p>
        <p>In England we have American TV shows, American pop groups and American movies, yet the language is not changed to suit us. The spell-checks on our computers come in American English. Britain hardly has any popular entertainment over here, and yet the Harry Potter books are Americanized. Whose language is it anyway?</p>
        <p>MARTHA BEDFORD  Huntington, N.Y., July 10, 2000</p>
      </block>
    </body.content>
